				<li id="16718613" class="cmnt-root" data="-20" data-d="1655690592000"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment-box"><div class="avatar"><img src="/images/avatar.png" alt="" /><div class="comment-username">Anonymous</div></div><div class="comment"><div class="title"><span class="txt-subject"></span><input style="display: none;" class="txt-subject-ed"><span class="right cmt-ui"><a href="https://fextralife.com/forums/t578449/Black-Flame-Blade" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">19 Jun 2022 22:03</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class="report-post" href="https://fextralife.com/forums/report.php?f=193&p=16718613" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="report this post"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-flag" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></span></div><p class="txt-comment">I know the chances of Elden Ring dev teams checking Fextralife for balance update ideas is probably 1%, but here is my proposed change for Blackflame Blade. Make it cost about 30 FP, but what it does is create 5 or so temporary items (similar to how invading generates 3 phantom fingers, so I know coding for this could exist in the game at least). These items would essentially be like the pine bundles/drawstring grease, but a black flame version. You could also set a permanent quickslot in your inventory for when you create more via the spell. They have the exact same duration and effect as normal, and rest inside your inventory untill you die or use them all, which it needs to be recasted to create more.<br/><br/>I&apos;ve done a full playthrough doing a Blackflame Blade build, and even used it in PVP a lot, and this would change 99% of my problems with this spell while keeping the core mechanic of it intact: <br/><br/>1: efficient FP to damage/usefulness to compete with the other buffs, as long as you think tactically about when to apply and attack<br/>2: it still keeps it&apos;s niche of being a short-lived but extremely efficient debuff to large HP targets, needing to be applied at just the right time to counterattack or apply pressure to players, as the burn can catch them even if they roll<br/>3: buff builds in general tend to be almost entirely focused on actual melee combat, so having to invest so much mind (i found 20 to be a decent sweetspot personally, but it&apos;s still quite a lot) is counter-intuitive. this change would greatly benefit that playstyle without compromising what Fromsoft intended with this spell as explained above</p><textarea style="display: none;" class="txt-comment-ed"></textarea><div class="clearfix"><a role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#zz-16718613" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Reply</a><a id="btnExpandComment" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#replies-16718613" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Replies (<span class="replies">0</span>)</a><div class="vote pull-right"><section class="t-up"><span></span><p>3</p><i class="add">+1</i></section><section class="t-down"><span></span><p>23</p><i class="sub">-1</i></section></div></div><div class="collapse-com transparent"><div class="col-trigger collapse" id="zz-16718613"><div class="ng-scope"><textarea id="dcomment" class="ng-pristine ng-untouched ng-invalid ng-invalid-required" placeholder="Input your comments:"></textarea><button id="btn-16718613" class="btn btn-default btnPostReply"><i class="glyphicon glyphicon-pencil"></i> Submit</button><img id="newCommentAvatar" src="/images/avatar.png"/></div></div></div></div><div class="clearfix"></div><ul class="children collapse" id="replies-16718613"></ul></li></ul></li>
			
